 januari 1170 to 7 januari 1171","1117–1170":"1117–van8januari1170to7januari1171","1122–Male":"1122–Overleden","1145–1225":"1145–1225","1136–Male":"1136–Overleden","1140–1191":"1140–1191","–1184":"–1184","1089–Male":"1089–Overleden","1091–1144":"1091–1144","1091":"1091","about 1140":"circa 1140","before 1117":"vóór 1117","1184":"1184","1140":"1140","1170":"van 8 januari 1170 to 7 januari 1171","1191":"1191","1117":"1117","1138":"1138","1225":"1225","1136":"1136","1145":"1145","about 1117":"circa 1117","1144":"1144","1089":"1089","1122":"1122","about 1136":"circa 1136","Europe":"Europa","England":"England","Westmorland, England":"Westmorland, England","Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1117–1170":"about 1117–from 8 January 1170 to 7 January 1171","1117–1170":"1117–from8January1170to7January1171","1122–Male":"1122–Deceased","1145–1225":"1145–1225","1136–Male":"1136–Deceased","1140–1191":"1140–1191","–1184":"–1184","1089–Male":"1089–Deceased","1091–1144":"1091–1144","1091":"1091","about 1140":"about 1140","before 1117":"before 1117","1184":"1184","1140":"1140","1170":"from 8 January 1170 to 7 January 1171","1191":"1191","1117":"1117","1138":"1138","1225":"1225","1136":"1136","1145":"1145","about 1117":"about 1117","1144":"1144","1089":"1089","1122":"1122","about 1136":"about 1136","Europe":"Europe","England":"England","Westmorland, England":"Westmorland, England","Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lancaster","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Lancaster in northwestern England, which is recorded as <i>Loncastre</i> in 1086. The place takes its name from the river Lune + Old English <i>ceaster</i> ‘city, Roman fortification’ (from Latin <i>castra</i> ‘legionary camp’). The river name is probably British, perhaps related to Gaelic <i>slán</i> ‘healthy’, ‘salubrious’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Lancaster I was born about 1117, in Cumberland, England, his father, Gilbert de Montanis de Furnesio, was 30 and his mother, Goditha Elftredsdatter, was 28. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Gundred de Warenne. In 1138, at the age of 22, his occupation is listed as castellan of william fitz duncan's castle of egremont 1138. He died from 8 January 1170 to 7 January 1171, in Westmorland, England."},"et":{"about 1117–1170":"umbes 1117–8. jaanuar 1170 kuni 7. jaanuar 1171","1117–1170":"